subsection.p:
Matrix notation gives us a convenient way of representing the 2 \times 2 system. If we let 
            A =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            a & b \\
            c & d
            \end{pmatrix}
            \quad\text{and}\quad
            {\mathbf x}(t)
            =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            x(t) \\ y(t)
            \end{pmatrix},
        then we can rewrite our system as
            \begin{pmatrix}
            x'(t) \\ y'(t)
            \end{pmatrix}
            =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            ax(t) + b y(t) \\ cx(t) + d y(t)
            \end{pmatrix}
            =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            a & b \\
            c & d
            \end{pmatrix}
            \begin{pmatrix}
            x(t) \\ y(t)
            \end{pmatrix}.
        In other words, we can write our system as
            \frac{d \mathbf x}{dt} = A {\mathbf x},
        where
            \mathbf x' = \frac{d \mathbf x}{dt} = \begin{pmatrix} x'(t) \\ y'(t) \end{pmatrix}.

introduction.p:
Consider the initial value problem d\mathbf x/dt = A \mathbf x, where

                        A \amp  = \begin{pmatrix} 23 \amp 10 \\-50 \amp -22 \end{pmatrix}

                        \mathbf x(0) \amp = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 3  \end{pmatrix}.

statement.p:
Use the fact that
                        \mathbf x(0) = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2  \end{pmatrix}
                    to find c_1 and c_2 such that \mathbf x(t) = c_1 e^{\lambda t} \mathbf v_1 + c_2 e^{\mu t} \mathbf v_2 is a solution to the initial-value problem.  Does this solution agree with the solution that you plotted in ?

Prove that
                    \alpha e^{\lambda t} \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} + \beta e^{\lambda t} \begin{pmatrix} t \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}
                is the general solution of 
                    {\mathbf x}' 
                    =
                    \begin{pmatrix}
                    \lambda & 1 \\
                    0 & \lambda
                    \end{pmatrix}
                    {\mathbf x}.
